So far we have assumed the MFI behaves so as to maximize outreach and with that lower costs and increase benefits to pass on all the gains in surplus to the average borrower.  This would be consistent with the behavior of a non-profit that cannot distribute profits and whose incentives are aligned to maximize borrower welfare because of the `social mission' orientation of its principal shareholders.  The MFI is able to sustain itself over time but the rate of return on equity is $\mathrm{\gammaup }$, the same rate return as investments in other areas of the economy. 

An intermediary with a profit motive will seek to earn an expected rate of return on equity in excess of $\mathrm{\gammaup }$. 
\begin{equation} \label{15)} 
p\frac{m}{\Delta } =\beta I_{m} +m+\frac{F}{N}  
\end{equation} 

We can interpret $\mathrm{\betaup }$ as the expected return on equity:
\begin{equation} \label{15)} 
\begin{array}{rcl} {E[R.O.E.\, ]\, \, \, \beta } & {=} & {\frac{{\rm Expected\; Profits}}{{\rm Equity}} } \\ {} & {=} & {\frac{N\left[pR-pR_{u} -m-F/N\right]}{NI_{m} } } \\ {} & {=} & {\frac{\left[pR_{m} -m-F/N\right]}{I_{m} } } \\ {\beta } & {=} & {\frac{\left[\frac{pm}{\Delta } -m-F/N\right]}{I_{m} } } \end{array} 
\end{equation} 
The ROE is $\mathrm{\gammaup }$ when intermediary's IC constraint binds.  If however intermediary capital is scarce, they will be able to earn a rent $\mathrm{\betaup }$$\mathrm{>}$$\mathrm{\gammaup }$.  This will be associated with a lower \textit{I${}_{m}$${}_{\ }$}(i.e. higher leverage).  Appendix 2 explores this scenario in further detail{\dots}

